SIMPLE: expatriate
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Expatriate
<hw>Ex*pa"tri*ate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.
& p. p.</pos> <conjf>Expatriated</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Expatriating</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[LL.
<ets>expatriatus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>expatriare</ets>; L. <ets>ex</ets>
out + <ets>patria</ets> fatherland, native land, fr. <ets>pater</ets>
father. See <er>Patriot</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To banish; to
drive or force (a person) from his own country; to make an exile
of.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>expatriated</qex> landed interest of France.</q>
<rj><qau>Burke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Reflexively, as <xex>To expatriate one's self</xex>:
To withdraw from one's native country; to renounce the rights and
liabilities of citizenship where one is born, and become a citizen of
another country.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Expatriation</ent>⟦br⟧
